<HEADLINE>
NCU LAUNCHES FORUM ON REMOTE SENSING
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March  19 (CNA) 03/19/07  19:18:22 (By Zep Hu)
</P>
<P>
A five-day academic forum on remote sensing opened Monday at
National Central University (NCU) in Chungli, Taoyuan County to
discuss the environment of Taiwan, Asian countries and the world,
sources from the university's Center for Space and Remote Sensing
Research said that day.
</P>
<P>
Attended by 150 researchers who have presented some 100 research
papers, the forum, will focus on areas of atmospheric,
hydrologic, geological and oceanological studies, as well as the
process of remote sensing data.
</P>
<P>
Event convener Chen Kun-shan, who is a professor at the center,
noted that in wake of drastic global climate changes, remote
sensing technology can provide real-time environmental data,
enhancing the efficacy and efficiency of environmental
management.
</P>
<P>
In Taiwan, located in an area facing constant threats of typhoon
and earthquake, advanced remote sensing capabilities are urgently
needed for greater accuracy in weather forecast and rapid
response in damage control, he said.
</P>
